courses.learning_outcomes:
 The ability to build sound cultural questions over contemporary theatre phenomena;
 The ability to READ, SEE, LISTEN and SMELL in and out of the cultural fabrics woven in the process of theatre making;
 The ability to appreciate THE POWER OF ADAPTATION in cultural and theatre development.

On successful completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:
1. Explain the concern of other-than-human animal with cultural studies perspective;
2. Identify the key issues and critical assessment of human-animal relationship;
3. Understand the approach in studying culture, animal and environment;
4. Enrich the angle of analyzing human living and animal species.

• Become acquainted with the basic issues of contemporary culture;
• Understand the perspectives of interdisciplinary in cultural studies;
• Realize to discuss cultural and social issues in critical ways;
• Understand the key theoretical concepts in cultural studies.

• Basic approaches to art appreciation and analysis;
• Over all understanding of the curatorial practice, from generating curatorial ideas to the final implementation;
• Creative thinking, both creative and intellectual, in conceiving curatorial ideas;
• Technical and managerial skills in implementing various types of exhibitions;
• Critical review in the practice, cultural values and ethics of curatorship.

Learning Outcomes
1. An understanding of the objectives, philosophy and ethical concerns;
2. Learning of the technical skills in organizing and monitoring community arts;
3. Nurturing creative skills in curating community arts projects dealing with specific community and issues.
At the end of the course, students will be able to
1. Understand the nature of community arts, its history and its various schools of thoughts;
2. Able to take the initiative of organizing events responding to community needs;

Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to:
Reflect upon key concepts and debates related to media art and technology and curatorial practices and applications of technologies in artistic and curatorial practice.
Reflect on how advanced technologies such as the internet, social media, AR/VR, AI and blockchain technologies have transformed curatorial and artistic practices.
Critically analyse and evaluate artworks, artistic practices and exhibitions employing advanced technologies and their conceptual underpinnings and methods of presentation;
Reflect upon the development of art and technology in relationship to technological innovation and art historical discourses;
Design and create a proposal and plan for an online/offline exhibition including developing a curatorial concept, selecting artists and artworks, creating an exhibition design and user journey, a technical implementation plan, and public programmes plan.

Course activities involve:
1. Researching various urban narratives, whether mainstream or personal;
2. Observing with photography and mapping such narratives;
3. Critical and independent thinking on the meaning of those narrative with essays / digital journal;
4. Producing reflections and commentary through mini films. (5-10mins.)
Through active production of images, students learn through the logistic of production to move away from passive consumer of images to creative producer of visions, taking hold of lifestyle directions within the urban environment and communicate such ideas to others engagingly and effectively.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. Introduction
PART I: HISTORICAL OVERVIEW
2. The Republican Period
Readings:
 Michael Sullivan, Art and Artists of Twentieth-century China (U of Cal P, 1996), 5–41;
 Tani Barlow, “Commercial Advertising Art in 1840-1940s ‘China,’” in Powers and Tsiang ed. A Companion to Chinese Arts (John Wiley & Sons, 2016), 431–453;
 林木： ＜現代中國國畫史上的嶺南派及廣東畫壇＞《朵雲》第59集 （2003）：24–57.
3. The Socialist Period
Readings:
 毛澤東：＜在延安文藝座談會上的講話＞
 Julia F. Andrews and Kuiyi Shen, The Art of Modern China (U of California P, 2012), 161–182;
 Tang Xiaobing, Visual Culture in Contemporary China (Cambridge UP, 2015), 18–60.
 Paul Clark, Chinese Cinema: Culture and Politics since 1949 (Press Syndicate, 1984), 94–124;
4. The Post-socialist Period
Readings:
 Wu Hung, Contemporary Chinese Art: A History: 1970s – 2000s (London: Thames & Hudson, 2014); 180–219;
 高明潞: 《牆 : 中國當代藝術的歷史與邊界》(北京 : 中國人民大學出版社2006), 17–59;
 Lin Xiaoping, Children of Marx and Coca-Cola: Chinese Avant-Garde Art and Independent Cinema (Honolulu: University of Hawaii Press, 2010), 33-56.
5. Group Discussion I
PART II: THEMES & STYLE
6. History and Revolution
Readings:
 Shaoqian Zhang, “Visualizing the Modern Chinese Party-State: From Political Education to Propaganda Agitation in the Early Republic Period,” in Twentieth-Century China 41, no 1 (2016): 52–80;
 Wang Ban, The Sublime Figure of History (Stanford UP, 1997), 194 – 228;
 Guo Wu, “Recalling Bitterness: Historiography, Memory and Myth in Maoist China” Twentieth-Century China 39, no. 3 (2014): 245–268;
 Ho, Denise and Jie Li, “From Landlord Manor to Red Memorabilia: Reincarnations of a Chinese Museum Town,” Modern China, (2015): 1–35.
7. People and Body
Readings:
 Ralph A. Litzinger, “Theorizing Postcolonialism: Reflections on the Politics of Marginality in Contemporary China” South Atlantic Quarterly 101, no. 1 (2002): 33–55;
 段以建: ＜論林風眠仕女畫對佛教壁畫的借鑒與創新＞《 南京藝術學院學報》 2014, no. 6: 72–74;
 陳荒煤，＜論正面人物形象的創造＞， 羅藝軍編《1920 – 1989中國電影理論文選，上冊》(文化藝術出版社，1992)，360–377；
 孫沛東，《時尚與政治：廣東民眾日常著裝時尚（1966-1976）》（北京：人民出版社，2013），142-166.
8. Nature and Landscape
Readings:
 吳冠中，《永無坦途》（香港：中和，2016），113–152;
 李可染： ＜漫談山水畫＞（1959）；載赫之輝編《李可染山水畫講義》（天津古籍出版社, 2009）：25–34;
 李小山: ＜中國現代繪畫的先驅＞；載鄭朝，金尚義編《林風眠論》（浙江美術出版社, 1990）：136–140;
 Lin Xiaoping, “Challenging the Canon: Socialist Realism in Traditional Chinese Painting Revisited,” Third Text 21, no. 1 (Jan 2007): 41–53.
9. Group Discussion II
10. Modernization and Technology
Readings:
 Michael Dutton, “Fragments of the Political, or How We Dispose of Wonder,” Social Text 110 (Spring 2012): 109–41;
 Tina Mai Chen, “The Human-Machine Continuum in Maoism: The Intersection of Soviet Socialist Realism, Japanese Theoretical Physics, and Chinese Revolutionary Theory,” Cultural Critique 80 (Winter 2012): 151–18；
 Laikwan Pang, “Tian Han’s Historical Dramas in the Great Leap Forward Period: History, State, and Authorship,” in Rojas & Bachner ed. Oxford Handbook of Chinese Literature (Oxford UP, 2016).
11. Realisms
Readings:
 Laikwan Pang, The Distorting Mirror: Visual Modernity in China (U. of Hawaii P.), 33–65;
 Weihong Du, “A Turning Point for Guohua? Xu Beihong and Transformative Encounters with the Socialist Spirit: 1933–1953” Twentieth-Century China 39, no. 3 (2014): 216–244;
 David Dewei Wang, The Lyrical in Epic Time: Modern Chinese Intellectuals and Arts through the 1949 Crisis (Columbia UP, 2015), 237–270;
 Boris Groys, The Total Art of Stalinism: Avant-Garde, Aesthetic Dictatorship, and Beyond (Verso, 2011), 14–74;
 汪介之，＜“社會主義現實主義”在中國的理論行程＞《南京師範大學文學院學報》2012年3月第1期：143–157.
12. Lecture & Review

courses.learning_outcomes:
- Engage in cultural/political analysis of texts and images using theories of representation;
- Acquire critical familiarity with the uses and limitations of major theoretical approaches and frameworks for culture/political analysis of popular culture/social settings;
- Acquire practical knowledge and skills required for cultural commentators and analysts in applying theoretical tools and artifacts in varying social contexts
